Project: Investigate Dataset of No-Show for Medical appoinments in brazil.¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Limitations
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This is a data analysis of 100K medical appoinments in brazil in the period between April to June of 2016. This dataset is oriented about whether the patient showed up for the appoinment or not. It contains data about (PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age, Neighbourhood, scholarship i.e insurance, if the patient has any of Hypertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handicapped, if they recived SMS, and lastely and most importantly the No-show data (kindly notice here: yes or 1 here means that they didn't show up!).

Visit this dataset in kaggle.com or download it directly!

Research Questions:
1- What is the rate of show vs no-show?
2- What is the gender percentage?
3- How did medical diseases affected the rate of show vs no-show?
4- How did Age affected the rate of show vs no-show?
5- How did receving a SMS message affected the rate of show vs no-show?
6- How did having a scholarship(i.e. insurance) affected the rate of show vs no-show?
7- How did Neighbourhood affected the rate of show vs no-show?
8- How did receving SMS affect the ratio of no-show between males and females?
9- How did Hypertension affected the ratio of not showing up males and females?
10- How did Alcoholism affected the ratio of not showing up males and females?
11- How did Diabetes affected the ratio of not showing up males and females?

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

What is the rate of show vs no-show?¶

In [251]:
#splitting data frame to show and non-show data frames
No_show = df[df['No_show'] == 1]
show = df[df['No_show'] == 0]
In [252]:
#pie charting the precentage of show vs non_show data
df_pie = df['No_show'].value_counts()
mylabels = ["Showed-up", "Didnt show up"]
noshow = df_pie.plot.pie(labels = mylabels, figsize=(10,10), autopct='%1.2f%%', fontsize = 12)
noshow.set_title('No show (%) \n', fontsize = 15);

This pie chart shows that 22.52% of appointments; the patient didn't show up!

How did Age affected the rate of show vs no-show?¶

Age data is only significant for age group from 10-30 years and 80-100 years; ratio of not showing up is higher than the other ages!

In the two last pie charts: Diabetic females are likely to not show up more than Diabetic males!

So in general: females who have medical diseases (except for ALocoholism) didn't show up more than males.

Limitations¶


1 - We've removed a data entry from the original dataset. Original size 110527 and new size: 110526. And also there are 3539 data entries in which Age is defined by zero and we don't exactly know if they are not real data or they're just new-borns.
2- Only 32% of the appointments had SMS messages received and they didn't show-up more than who didn't recevie sms. Maybe they were encouraged to enroll in SMS notifications after Non-showing up for their appointment. And patients who registered for SMS happens to have problems making appointments.

Conclusions¶

By the end of this analysis we found out that this data which contains more than 100K medical appointment records that 22.52% of apointments, patient didn't show-up.¶



Show-up rates didn't get affected by:¶

1- Gender:¶

35% of patients were males, and the ratio of male patients who didn't show-up was around 35% also (34.6%).¶

2- Medical diseases:¶

Hypertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism and Handicapp.¶



Show-up rates got affected by:¶

1- Age:¶

Age groups from 10-30 years and 80-100 years; ratio of not showing up is higher than the other ages!¶

2- SMS:¶

The ratio between (Males not showing up after not receving a SMS reminder) to (Males not showing up after receving a sms) is higher than Females ones!¶

3- Scholarship:¶

Patients who had had a scholarship didn't show-up more!¶

4- Some Neighbourhoods:¶

as JESUS DE NAZARETH, TABUAZEIRO and ITARARÉ, showed higher no show-up ratio than others.¶



Females who have medical diseases (except for ALocoholism) didn't show up more than males.¶
